# 🐧 Linux Theory

## Linux File Permissions Review

Every file and directory in Linux has three permission categories:

- Owner
- Group
- Others

Permission Types:

- Read (r)
- Write (w)
- Execute (x)

Example:

-rwxr-xr--

Owner has full access.

Group has read and execute.

Others have read only.

---

## chmod

Used to change file permissions.

Examples

```bash
chmod 755 file1
chmod 644 file2
chmod 777 file3
```

---

## chown

Changes file ownership.

Example

```bash
sudo chown user:user filename
```

---

# Special Permissions

## 1. SUID (Set User ID)

Symbol:

```text
s
```

Purpose:

When a user executes a file with SUID enabled, the program runs with the permissions of the file owner instead of the current user.

Example

```bash
ls -l /usr/bin/passwd
```

Output

```text
-rwsr-xr-x
```

The `passwd` command runs with root privileges so users can securely change their passwords.

---

## 2. SGID (Set Group ID)

Purpose

Files:

Runs with the permissions of the file's group.

Directories:

New files inherit the directory's group ownership.

Useful for shared project directories.

---

## 3. Sticky Bit

Symbol

```text
t
```

Purpose

Users can delete only their own files inside a shared directory.

Example

```bash
ls -ld /tmp
```

Output

```text
drwxrwxrwt
```

The `/tmp` directory allows everyone to create files but prevents users from deleting files created by others.

